answers.body_markdown:
Try doing the `progressBar1.PerformStep();` on the UI thread by Invoking it, like below

    BeginInvoke((MethodInvoker)delegate
    {
        progressBar1.PerformStep();
    });

And remove the `Application.DoEvents();`

Why don&#39;t you use the background workers [`ReportProgress`-method](https://docs.microsoft.com/en-us/dotnet/api/system.componentmodel.backgroundworker.reportprogress)? It exists for exactly this purpose.

Subscribe to the [`ProgressChanged`-event](https://docs.microsoft.com/en-us/dotnet/api/system.componentmodel.backgroundworker.progresschanged) and update the progress-bar from there.

```
// Wherever you instanciate your BackgroundWorker
backgroundWorker1.ProgressChanged += (o, e) =&gt; progressBar1.Value = e.ProgressPercentage;
```

```
// Your DoWork method
private void BackgroundWorker1_DoWork(object sender, DoWorkEventArgs e)
{
    for (int i = 1; i &lt;= 100; i++)
    {
        Convert();
        backgroundWorker1.ReportProgress(i);
    }
    // Bitrate();
}
```

Since these steps are in percent you should also set the minimum and maximum value of the progress bar. You already set the value and the step but you shouldn&#39;t do it in the `DoWork`-method. Do it somewhere else, for example just before calling `backgroundWorker1.RunWorkerAsync()`.  
Also note that I made the for loop 1-100 since we&#39;re working with percent. You could also do 0-99 and report i+1.

```
progressBar1.Value = 0;
progressBar1.Step = 1;
progressBar1.Minimum = 0;
progressBar1.Maximum = 100;
```

Edit 1:

As mentionend in the comments, I forgot the possibility of creating a `BackgroundWorker` with the winforms designer. In that case, you should use the constructor of your Form (or UserControl) to subscribe to the `ProcessChanged` event.

Edit 2:

To answer your follow-up question on resetting the ProgressBar after the worker has completed, I will show you two possible solutions.

```
// You can directly subscribe to RunWorkerCompleted using a lambda like before
backgroundWorker1.RunWorkerCompleted += (o, e) =&gt; progressBar1.Value = 0;
```

```
// Or you can use a method (useful if you have other things to do when the worker is done)
private void backgroundWorker1_RunWorkerCompleted(object sender, RunWorkerCompletedEventArgs e)
{
    progressBar1.Value = 0;
    // some more stuff
}

// Subscribe to RunWorkerCompleted with this method
backgroundWorker1.RunWorkerCompleted += backgroundWorker1_RunWorkerCompleted;
```

In both solutions, the subscription to `RunWorkerCompleted` should be put right before or after the subscription to `ProgressChanged` (this means in the constructor in this case).

