The error says it all: you can&#39;t use unexported fields. Change the fields of `Coordinate` to be exported:

    type Coordinate struct {
    	X float64
    	Y float64
    	Z float64
    }

Then it&#39;ll work, and outputs (try it on the [Go Playground][1]):

    (1.000000,2.000000,3.000000)
    {[0 0 0 0 0 0 240 63 0 0 0 0 0 0 0 64 0 0 0 0 0 0 8 64] 0 0}
    (1.000000,2.000000,3.000000)
    over

Also never omit errors in Go. [`binary.Read()`][2] and [`binary.Write()`][3] return errors, always check them, for example:

	if err := binary.Write(&amp;buf, binary.LittleEndian, &amp;point); err != nil {
		// Handle error, for brevity we just panic here:
		panic(err)
	}

	if err := binary.Read(&amp;buf, binary.LittleEndian, p); err != nil {
		// Handle error, for brevity we just panic here:
		panic(err)
	}


  [1]: https://play.golang.org/p/cELBd55Rqw_w
  [2]: https://golang.org/pkg/encoding/binary/#Read
  [3]: https://golang.org/pkg/encoding/binary/#Write

